04173nam a22006015i 9780226582689DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265826897 a10.7208/97802265826892doi  a(DE-B1597)524913  a(OCoLC)1054645980  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPR2995b.L47 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a822.332231 aLerer, Seth, eauthor.10aShakespeare's Lyric Stage :bMyth, Music, and Poetry in the Last Plays /cSeth Lerer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tA Note on Texts, Editions, and Critical Traditions -- t1. Myth, Music, and Lyric -- t2. An Elegy for Ariel -- t3. Poetry and Performance in Th e Winter's Tale -- t4. Pageantry, Power, and Lyricism in Henry VIII -- t5. Aesthetic Judgment and the Audience in Cymbeline -- tEpilogue: Lyric Recognition and the Editorial Romance in Pericles and The Two Noble Kinsmen -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to have an emotional response to poetry and music? And, just as important but considered less often, what does it mean not to have such a response? What happens when lyric utterances-which should invite consolation, revelation, and connection-somehow fall short of the listener's expectations? As Seth Lerer shows in this pioneering book, Shakespeare's late plays invite us to contemplate that very question, offering up lyric as a displaced and sometimes desperate antidote to situations of duress or powerlessness. Lerer argues that the theme of lyric misalignment running throughout The Tempest, The Winter's Tale, Henry VIII, and Cymbeline serves a political purpose, a last-ditch effort at transformation for characters and audiences who had lived through witch-hunting, plague, regime change, political conspiracies, and public executions. A deep dive into the relationship between aesthetics and politics, this book also explores what Shakespearean lyric is able to recuperate for these "victims of history" by virtue of its disjointed utterances. To this end, Lerer establishes the concept of mythic lyricism: an estranging use of songs and poetry that functions to recreate the past as present, to empower the mythic dead, and to restore a bit of magic to the commonplaces and commodities of Jacobean England. Reading against the devotion to form and prosody common in Shakespeare scholarship, Lerer's account of lyric utterance's vexed role in his late works offers new ways to understand generational distance and cultural change throughout the playwright's oeuvre.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aDowland. 4aFirst Folio. 4aOrpheus. 4aOvid. 4aShakespeare. 4alast plays. 4alyric poetry. 4amusic. 4amyth. 4aravishment. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226582689423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226582689.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles